'''Barrow-in-Furness''' ([[Cumbric language|Cumbric]]: Barragh-yn-Faiddis), often known simply as '''Barrow''', is an [[manufacturing|industrial town]] and [[seaport]] which forms about half the territory of the wider [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]] in the county of [[Cumbria]], [[England]]. It lies {{convert|100.2|mi|km|0}} northwest of [[Manchester]] and {{convert|54|mi|km|0}} south southwest from the [[county town]] of [[City of Carlisle|Carlisle]]. The town is situated at the tip of the [[Furness|Furness peninsula]] bordered only by [[Morecambe Bay]] and the [[Irish Sea]]. Barrow is located just over {{convert|220|mi}} north-west of London and {{convert|60|mi}} south of the [[Anglo-Scottish border|Scottish border]].

[[Historic counties of England|Historically]] a part of [[Lancashire]], Barrow was a small fishing village before the arrival of the [[Industrial Revolution]] in the mid-19th century. The building of the [[Furness Railway]] allowed iron ore to be transported to the area; the village's location made it ideal for smelting and then exporting steel. The natural harbour the booming town possessed allowed the locally produced steel to be put to another use: shipbuilding.<ref>[http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/mission.htm Barrow Museum Mission Statement], The Dock Museum Website. URL accessed 11 December 2006.</ref> 

The shipyard became a significant producer of naval vessels and from the 1960s increasingly specialised in the construction of nuclear-powered submarines. The original iron- and steel- making enterprises closed down after [[World War II]], leaving boat building the area's main industry and employer. All of Britain's [[Vanguard class submarine]]s, which carry [[UK Trident program|Trident]] nuclear weapons, were manufactured at the facility. With the end of the [[Cold War]] and subsequent decrease in military spending the town suffered high unemployment, though the shipyard remains operational and the largest submarine production facility in the UK.<ref name="unemployment" /> 

==Toponymy==
The name was originally that of an island<U+2014>the name 'Barrai' can be traced back to 1190. This was later renamed 'Old Barrow', recorded as Oldebarrey in 1537, and Old Barrow Insula and Barrohead in 1577. The island was then joined to the mainland and the town took its name. The name itself seems to mean 'island with promontory', combining [[Brythonic languages|British]] ''barro-'' and [[Old Norse]] ''ey'', but it is more likely that Scandinavian settlers simply accepted ''barro-'' as a meaningless name, and so added an explanatory Old Norse second element.<ref>{{cite book |last= Mills|first= David|title= The Place Names of Lancashire|year= 1976|publisher= Batsford Books|location= London|isbn= 0 7134 3248 9}}</ref>

== History ==
In the [[Middle Ages]] the [[Furness|Furness peninsula]] was controlled by the Cistercian monks of the Abbey of St Mary of Furness, known as [[Furness Abbey]]. This was located in the 'Vale of Nightshade', now on the outskirts of the modern town.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=150#abbey | title=Local history and heritage | publisher=Barrow Borough Council | accessdate=2007-06-10 }}</ref> Originally founded for the [[Congregation of Savigny|Savigniac order]], it was built on the orders of [[Stephen of England|Stephen of Blois]] in 1123. Soon after the abbey's foundation the monks discovered iron ore deposits, later to prove the basis for the Furness economy. These thin layers, close to the surface, were extracted through open cut workings,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cumbria-industries.org.uk/ironmining.htm | title=Iron Mining | publisher=Industries of Cumbria | accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> which were then smelted by the monks in small [[bloomery|bloomeries]] (early furnaces).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fellsanddales.org.uk/trails/mineral_wealth.php#mineral_wealth | title=Mineral Wealth | publisher=Cumbria Fells and Dales LEADER+ Programme | accessdate=2007-06-10 }}</ref> The proceeds from mining, along with agriculture and fisheries, meant that by the 15th century the abbey had become the second richest and most powerful [[Cistercian|Cistercian abbey]] in England, after [[Fountains Abbey]] in Yorkshire.<ref>{{cite web | author=English Heritage | title=Furness Abbey| publisher=English Heritage | url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/server/show/ConProperty.149 | accessdate=2007-05-06 }}</ref>
However, Barrow itself was a hamlet in the parish of Dalton-in-Furness on the Furness peninsula reliant on the land and sea for survival. Small quantities of iron and ore were exported from jetties which were constructed into the channel separating the then-village and [[Walney Island]]. Amongst the oldest buildings in Barrow are several cottages and farm houses in [[Newbarns]] (now a [[Ward (country subdivision)|ward]] of the town) which date back to the early 1600s. Even as late as 1843 there were still only 32 dwellings including two pubs.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/pdf/summary%20of%20plan%20areas.pdf | title=Plan of Barrow 1843 | publisher=Barrow Borough Council | format=[[PDF]] | accessdate=2007-06-10 }}</ref> [[Image:FurnessAbbey.jpg|thumb|right|Furness Abbey]]

In 1839 [[Henry Schneider]] arrived as a young speculator and dealer in [[iron]], and he finally discovered large deposits of [[haematite]] in 1850. He and other investors founded the [[Furness Railway]], the first section of which opened in 1846 to transport the ore from the slate quarries at [[Kirkby-in-Furness]] and haematite mines at [[Lindal-in-Furness]] to a deep water harbour near [[Roa Island]].<ref name="railway">{{cite web | url =http://www.furnessrailwaytrust.org.uk/frco.htm | title = History of the Furness Railway Company | publisher = The Furness Railway Trust | accessdate = 2007-07-08}}</ref> The docks built between 1867 and 1881 in the more sheltered channel between the mainland and [[Barrow Island (England)|Barrow Island]] replaced the port at [[Roa Island]]. The increasing quantities of iron ore mined in Furness were then brought to Barrow to be transported by sea.

The investors in the burgeoning mining and railway industries decided greater profits could be made by smelting the iron ore into steel, and then exporting the finished product. Schneider and [[Sir James Ramsden|James Ramsden]], the railway's general manager, erected blast furnaces at Barrow that by 1876 formed the largest [[steelworks]] in the world at the time.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/about_us/ironbridge_archaeology/projects/barrow/|title= Barrow|accessdate=2007-08-25 |publisher= [[Ironbridge Gorge]] Museum Trust}}</ref> Its success was a result of the availability of local iron ore, coal from the [[Cumberland]] mines and easy rail and sea transport. The Furness Railway, who counted local aristocrats [[William Cavendish, 7th Duke of Devonshire|The Duke of Devonshire]] and the Duke of Buccleugh as investors, kick-started the Industrial Revolution on the peninsula. The railway brought mined ore to the town, where the steelworks produced large quantities of steel. It was used for shipbuilding or derived products such as rails were exported from the newly built docks.<ref name="railway"/> This caused Barrow's population, originally 700 in 1851, to reach 10,000 by 1864 and 47,000 by 1881, forty years after the railway was built.

[[Image:Barrow Works 1890.jpg|thumb|Barrow Shipbuilding Works circa. 1890]]
[[File:Cornmillcrossing.jpg|thumb|Cornmill Crossing in 1895 (one of many stations of the [[Furness Railway]]), a [[B&Q]] and [[JJB]] store and gym now exist on the site]]
[[File:Barro1940.jpg|thumb|The now demolished Buccleuch Street power station and Case's brewery circa. 1940]]

The sheltered straight between Barrow and [[Walney Island]] was an ideal location for the shipyard. The first ship to be built was the ''Jane Roper'', launched in 1852; the first steamship, a 3,000-ton liner named ''Duke of Devonshire'', in 1873. Shipbuilding activity increased, and on 18 February 1871 the Barrow Shipbuilding Company was incorporated. Barrow's relative isolation from the United Kingdom's industrial heartlands meant the newly formed company included several capabilities that would usually be subcontracted to other establishments. In particular, a large engineering works was constructed including a foundry and pattern shop, a forge, and an engine shop. In addition, the shipyard had a joiners' shop, a boat-building shed and a sailmaking and rigging loft.<ref name="barrow-works">{{cite book | last = The Naval and Armaments Company Limited | title = The Works at Barrow-in-Furness of The Naval Construction and Armaments Company Limited - Historical and Descriptive | publisher = The Naval and Armaments Company Limited, partly reprinted from 'Engineering' magazine | year = 1896 | location = Barrow-in-Furness | page = 54 }}</ref> 

During these boom years, Ramsden proposed building a planned town to accommodate the large workforce which had arrived. There are few [[town and country planning in the United Kingdom|planned towns]] in the United Kingdom, and Barrow is one of the oldest. Its centre contains a grid of well-built terraced houses, with long tree-lined roads leading away from central squares. Ramsden later became the first [[mayor]] of Barrow,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2490 |title= List of Mayors | publisher = Barrow Borough Council |accessdate=2007-07-06 }}</ref> which was given [[municipal borough]] status in 1867, and later [[county borough]] status in 1889.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dalton-in-furness.org.uk/dalton-online/history/modern-town/modern-town-localgov.html |title= History of Dalton-in-Furness |accessdate=2007-07-06 | work= Dalton Online|publisher= Dalton Community Association}}</ref> The imposing red sandstone Town Hall, designed by W.H. Lynn, was built in a [[neo-gothic]] style in 1887.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=150 | title = Local History and Heritage | publisher = Barrow Borough Council | accessdate = 2007-07-08 }}</ref> Prior to this, the borough council had met at the railway headquarters, the railway company's control of industry extended to the administration of the town itself.

The Barrow Shipbuilding Company was taken over by the [[Sheffield]] steel firm of [[Vickers]] in 1897, by which time the shipyard had surpassed the railway and steelworks as the largest employer and landowner in Barrow. The company constructed [[Vickerstown]], modelled on George Cadbury's [[Bournville]], on the adjacent [[Walney Island]] in the early twentieth century to house its employees.<ref>{{cite news | first=Frank | last=Partridge | coauthors= | title=The Compete Guide to: England's Islands | date=2006-03-16 | publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] | url =http://travel.independent.co.uk/uk/article351869.ece | work =[[The Independent]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-08-10 | language = }}</ref> It also commissioned [[Sir Edwin Lutyens]] to design [[Abbey House, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey House]] as a guest house and residence for its managing director at the time, Commander Craven.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.rotary-ribi.org/clubs/committee.asp?ClubCtteeID=2939&ClubID=1734 |title=The Rotary Club of Furness |accessdate=2007-08-10 |publisher=The Rotary Club of Great Britain }}</ref>

By the 1890s the shipyard was heavily engaged in the construction of warships for the [[Royal Navy]] and also for export. The [[Royal Navy|Navy]]'s first submarine, ''[[Holland 1]]'', was built in 1901,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.submarineheritage.com/history.html | title=Submarine History of Barrow-in-Furness | publisher=Submarine Heritage Centre | accessdate=2007-07-20 }}</ref> and by 1914 the UK had the most advanced submarine fleet in the world, with 94% of it constructed by Vickers. Vickers was also famous for the construction of [[airships]] ([[airship hangar]]) during the early 1900s.  [http://homepage.ntlworld.com/forgottenfutures/vickers/vickers.htm] Well-known ships built in Barrow include the [[Japanese battleship Mikasa|''Mikasa'']], Japanese flagship during the [[Russo-Japanese War]], the liner [[SS Oriana (1959)|SS ''Oriana'']] and the aircraft carriers [[HMS Invincible (R05)|HMS ''Invincible'']] and [[HMAS Melbourne (R21)|HMAS ''Melbourne'']].

During [[World War II]] Barrow was a target for the German airforce, the [[Luftwaffe]], looking to disable the town's shipbuilding capabilities (see [[Barrow Blitz]]).<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/bob1940/september2.html |title=The Battle of Britain - Diary - 2 September 1940 |accessdate=2007-08-05 |date=2005-02-16 |publisher=[[RAF]] }}</ref> The town suffered the most in a short period between April and May 1941. During the war, a local housewife, [[Nella Last]], was selected to write a diary of her everyday experiences on the home front for the [[Mass-Observation]] project. Her memoirs were later adapted for television as ''[[Housewife, 49]]'' starring [[Victoria Wood]]. The difficulty in targeting bombs meant that the shipyards and steelworks were often missed, at the expense of the residential areas. Ultimately, 83 people were killed and 11,000 houses in the area were left damaged. To escape the heaviest bombardments, many people in the central areas left the town to sleep in hedgerows with some being permanently evacuated. Barrow's industry continued to supply the war effort, with [[Winston Churchill]] visiting the town on one occasion to launch the aircraft carrier [[HMS Indomitable (R92)|HMS ''Indomitable'']].<ref name="dock">{{cite web |url= http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/docs/Publication%20world%20war%20II-web.pdf|title= World War II|accessdate=2007-08-25|date=2005-02-16 |format= PDF|publisher= [[Dock Museum]]}}</ref>

The end of the war saw the beginning of a long decline of ore mining and steel-making as a result of overseas competition and dwindling resources. The Barrow ironworks closed in 1963,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nwda.co.uk/docs/Project_Corus_July05.doc|title= Project Corus (Workington) Steering Group Report|accessdate=2007-08-31 |date=  2005-06-01|format= [[DOC (computing)|DOC]]|publisher= Northwest Development Agency}}</ref> three years after the last Furness mine shut. The then small steelworks followed suit in 1983<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.banklands.com/Barrow%20Steel.htm | title=Barrow Steel | accessdate = 2007-07-21 }}</ref> leaving Barrow's shipyard as the town's principal industry. From the 1960s onwards it concentrated its efforts in [[submarine]] manufacture, and the UK's first [[nuclear-powered submarine]], [[HMS Dreadnought (S101)|HMS ''Dreadnought'']] was constructed in 1960. [[HMS Resolution|HMS ''Resolution'']], the [[Swiftsure class submarine|''Swiftsure''-class]], [[Trafalgar class submarine|''Trafalgar''-class]] and [[Vanguard class submarine|''Vanguard''-class]] submarines all followed.

[[Image:Battleship Mikasa.jpg|thumb|right|Mikasa in Japan in 2005]]
The end of the [[Cold War]] in 1991 marked a reduction in the demand for military ships and submarines, and the town entered a period of decline. The shipyard's dependency on military contracts at the expense of civilian and commercial engineering and shipbuilding meant it was particularly hard hit as government defence spending was reduced dramatically.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Maggie Mort |coauthors=Graham Spinardi |year=2004 |title=Defence and the decline of UK mechanical engineering - the case of Vickers at Barrow |journal=Business History |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=1<U+2013>22 |url=http://www.lancs.ac.uk/fass/centres/css/library/mortspindardi_defenceandecline |accessdate= 2007-07-21 |doi=10.1080/00076790412331270099 |format={{Dead link|date=June 2008}} &ndash; <sup>[http://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3ADefence+and+the+decline+of+UK+mechanical+engineering+-+the+case+of+Vickers+at+Barrow&as_publication=Business+History&as_ylo=2004&as_yhi=2004&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>}}</ref> As a result, the workforce shrank from 14,500 in 1990 to 5,800 in February 1995,<ref>{{Citation | publisher = [[Competition Commission]] | title = Views of main parties as part of report into British Aerospace PLC proposed merger with VSEL | date = 23 May 1995 | url = http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365c5.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref> with overall unemployment in the town over that period rising from 4.6% to 10%.<ref name="unemployment">{{cite web |url= http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365a4.8.pdf|title= Appendix on unemployment as part of report into British Aerospace PLC proposed merger with VSEL|accessdate=2007-08-31 |date=  1995-05-23|format= PDF|publisher= [[Competition Commission]]}}</ref> The rejection by the [[VSEL]] management of detailed plans for Barrow's industrial renewal in the mid-to-late 1980s remains a point of contention.<ref>{{cite book |last= Mort|first= Maggie|title= Building the Trident Network|year= 2002|publisher= [[MIT Press]]|isbn= 0 262 13397 0}}</ref> This has led to renewed academic attention in recent years to the possibilities of converting military-industrial production in declining shipbuilding areas to those in the offshore renewable energy sector.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.basicint.org/nuclear/beyondtrident/oceans.pdf|title= Oceans of Work: Arms Conversion Revisited|accessdate=2007-08-25 |last= Schofield|first= Steven|year= 2007|month= January|format= PDF|publisher= [[British American Security Information Council]]}}</ref>

In August 2002 Barrow suffered the [[2002 Barrow-in-Furness Legionnaires' disease outbreak|UK's worst ever outbreak of Legionnaires' Disease]]. There were 172 people reported to have caught the disease, of which seven ultimately died. This made it the fourth worst outbreak in the world in terms of number of cases and sixth worst in terms of deaths (see [[Legionellosis#Outbreaks of Legionnaires' disease|list of Legionnaires' disease outbreaks]]). The source of the virus was later found to be from steam coming out of a badly maintained air conditioning unit. The system was located in the council-run arts centre Forum 28, with the vent emitting the disease over a busy alleyway in the town centre.<ref>{{cite news | title = Legionnaires' source officially traced | publisher = BBC News | date = 2002-08-20 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2205186.stm | accessdate=2003-07-21 }}</ref> 

The coroner for Furness and South Cumbria criticised the council for its failings with regard to health and safety at the conclusion of an inquest into the seven deaths.<ref>{{cite news | title = A Total Shambles|publisher = [[North West Evening Mail]]| date = 2007-06-12 | url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508368 | accessdate = 2007-07-21 }}</ref> In 2006, council employee Gillian Beckingham and employer [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow Borough Council]] were cleared of seven charges of manslaughter, but both admitted breaching the Health and Safety at Work Act. Beckingham, the council senior architect ultimately responsible for health and safety at the centre, was fined <U+00A3>15,000 and the authority <U+00A3>125,000.<ref>{{cite news | title = Bug Death Council Worker Cleared | publisher = BBC News | date = 2006-07-31 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/5232086.stm | accessdate=2007-07-21 }}</ref> The borough council was the first public body in the country to have faced corporate manslaughter charges.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cipfa.org.uk/publicfinance/features_details.cfm?News_id=24043 | title =Back in the Line of Fire | publisher = www.publicfinance.co.uk | accessdate = 2007-07-21}}</ref>

== Regeneration ==
[[Image:Sunset from West Shore, Walney.JPG|thumb|An autumn sunset on [[Walney|West Shore Beach]], [[Walney]]]]

===The waterfront===
Many areas of the town have seen regeneration in the [[1990s]] and on 28 September 2007 Barrow's <U+00A3>200 million Dockland regeneration project began. Due to be completed by 2020, the project includes a new 'Barrow Marina Village' which will incorporate a <U+00A3>8 million 400-berth [[marina]], 600 houses, restaurants, shops, hotels and a new state of the art bridge across Cavendish Dock.{{Fact|date=June 2008}} A large watersports centre is also being built, with the possibility of a [[cruise ship]] terminal, some cruise ships are already scheduled to dock in Barrow mainly for tourists to visit the Lake District despite there still being no official cruise ship terminal. The [[Tahitian Princess]] is visiting port in May 2009.<ref>[http://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/news.cfm?ID=3166 http://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/news.cfm?ID=3166]</ref>

===Shipyard===
The shipyard has been given planning permission to construct a new {{convert|200|ft|m|abbr=on}} tall assembly hall, dubbed 'Son of DDH' in a reference to the existing Devonshire Dock Hall shipbuilding facility. However, the building will not now be used for the construction of [[aircraft carrier]] sections as the carrier build will now take place in Glasgow. [[John Hutton (Labour MP)|John Hutton]], MP for Barrow, has, however, promised that all seven Astute Class submarines will be built at the shipyard.<ref>{{cite news | title=Council go-ahead for 'Son of DDH' | date= 2007-08-17 | publisher=[[North West Evening Mail]] | url =http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=531927 |accessdate = 2007-08-18}}</ref> Following a decline in employment levels at the shipyard over the last 20 years, BAE recently announced that the current workforce of 3,835 could soon grow to 5,000, although this is still only a third of the 14,000 employed in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news | title=BAE Work Force Stats| date= 2007-12-31 | publisher=[[North West Evening Mail]] | url =http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=547314 }}</ref>

===Bridges===
[[Image:Donghai Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Donghai Bridge]] in [[Shanghai]], [[China]] has a similar structure to the proposed '''Morecambe Bay Bridge''']]

For many years there have been discussions whether or not to construct bridges across [[Morecambe Bay]] and the [[Duddon Estuary]], leading to the Build Duddon and Morecambe Bridges party contesting national elections in the borough of [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]], receiving 409 (1.1%) votes in the [[United Kingdom general election, 2005|2005 general election]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,,-10353,00.html|title= Timothy Bell|accessdate=2008-02-02 |publisher= ''[[The Guardian]]''}}</ref>

====Morecambe Bay bridge====
This project has recently received more coverage. Construction of the {{convert|12|mi|km|sing=on}} structure would create Europe's longest bridge and the [[List of bridges by length|7th longest in the world]]. Connecting [[Heysham]] in [[Lancashire]] to [[Rampside]], the bridge would also produce 200&nbsp;MW of renewable energy from a [[Tidal power#Tidal stream power|tidal stream system]], enough to power over 400,000 homes. The bridge would have a major economic impact on the area through increased employment and tourism, and would cut journeys to [[Manchester]] from Barrow from two hours down to under one, which would put Barrow within commuting range of a major city. The project's backer, Bridge Across the Bay Ltd., intends to seek planning permission in 2010. Subject to approval and the provision of finance, construction could begin around 2011, and the company estimates the bridge could be completed in 2015. [http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=509561&imageindex=0][http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/3723779.stm] The bridge is becoming ever more likely, as a second bridge to Walney Island from mainland Barrow is planned to relieve congestion, the [[Morecambe Bay]] bridge proposal is also being discussed by local councils[http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=584104].

====Duddon Estuary bridge====
A smaller bridge crossing the Duddon Estuary linking [[Askam]] and [[Millom]], would definitely help improve transport links to the area.{{Fact|date=December 2008}} There has also been talk of building a road and rail tunnel under the Duddon instead of a bridge.[http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=203923]

==Governance==
[[Image:Townhall Barrow.jpg|thumb|left|Barrow's iconic [[town hall]] at sunset.]]
Barrow is the largest town in the [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/673/1758/38265144918.xls | title = Cumbria's Population in Urban Areas 2003 | publisher = Cumbria County Council | format=[[Microsoft Excel|XLS]] | accessdate = 2006-12-11}}</ref> and the largest settlement in the peninsula of [[Furness]]. The borough is the direct inheritor of the municipal and county borough charters given to the town in the late 1800s.<ref name="mayorlist"> {{cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2490 |title=Barrow Borough Council - Former Mayors |accessdate=2007-08-18 |publisher=[[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow Borough Council]] }}</ref> Historically it is part of the [[Lonsdale (hundred)|Hundred of Lonsdale]] 'north of the sands' in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county boundaries]] of [[Lancashire]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043|title= Lancashire AncC: Historical Boundaries|accessdate=2007-03-09 |publisher= A Vision of Britain Through Time}}</ref> Since the local government reforms enacted in England in 1974 the town has been within the administrative [[shire county|shire]] and [[ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial county]] of [[Cumbria]]. It still forms a part of the official UK government administered [[Duchy of Lancaster]]. The [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow-in-Furness Borough Council]] forms the 'lower' tier of local government under [[Cumbria|Cumbria County Council]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Draft Statutory Instrument 2004 The Regional Assembly and Local Government Referendums (Date of Referendums, Referendum Question and Explanatory Material) (North West Region) Order 2004 | work=Office of Public Sector Information | url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/SI/si2004/draft/20049539.htm | accessdate = 2007-08-18}}</ref> The town, along with [[Walney Island]], is unparished and forms the bulk of the wards which make the entire borough's area. They can be seen in the box below.

