'''Country of birth'''<br />
The [[2001 UK census]] states that 93.56% (67,345) of the borough's population was born in England, 2.86% (2,061) in Scotland, 0.63% (451) in Wales, 0.68% (486) in [[Northern Ireland]], 0.32% (231) in the [[Republic of Ireland]] and 0.06% (43) in the [[Channel Islands]]. 0.61% (441) of the town's 2001 population were born in the rest of Europe, although numbers are likely to be currently much higher, due to significant immigration from [[Eastern Europe]] (in particular [[Poland]]) to Barrow. Barrow has the eighth fastest growing non-indigenous white community of any town or city in the country, at 15.9% growth between 2004 and 2005, only [[Exeter]], [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]], [[Colchester]], [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[Durham]], [[Leeds]] and [[Bristol]] were faster growing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/Product.asp?vlnk=14238|title= White Other Growth Rate|accessdate=2007-12-29 |work= Neighbourhood Statistics|publisher= National Statistics (statistics.gov.uk)}}</ref> Barrow has also seen a huge increase with other ethnic minority groups, and the growth rate for most groups is around 2 times faster than national average.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/Product.asp?vlnk=14238|title= Immigration Growth Rate|accessdate=2007-12-29 |work= Neighbourhood Statistics|publisher= National Statistics (statistics.gov.uk)}}</ref>. The [[Asia]]n born population represented 0.50% (363) of Barrow's population, 0.35% (253) of people were born in [[North America]], 0.23% (177) of people were born in [[Africa]], 0.12% (83) of people were born in [[Oceania]], 0.04% (27) of Barrovians were born in [[Latin American Briton|Latin America]], and 0.02% (11) of people were born in some other place.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=276911&c=LA14+3LD&d=13&e=13&g=431977&i=1x1003x1004&o=50&m=0&enc=1&dsFamilyId=11|title=Country of Birth|accessdate=2007-08-25 |year= 2001|month= April|work= Neighbourhood Statistics|publisher= National Statistics (statistics.gov.uk)}}</ref>

'''Religion'''<br />
In the 2001 census 58,322 Barrovians stated themselves as being [[Christian]]. People stating no religion or chose not to state numbered 13,234 combined. The second largest religion in Barrow is [[Islam]] with a population of 182 Muslims. Other religious populations are as follows: 72 [[Buddhists]], (nearby [[Kadampa Buddhist Temple|Conishead Priory]], the first [[Kadampa]] Buddhist centre in the west, is home to around 100 Buddhists<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.aboutulverston.co.uk/location/conisheadpriory.htm | title = Conishead Priory, Ulverston | accessdate=2007-07-21|publisher= AboutUlverston.co.uk}}</ref>) 46 [[Hindus]], 25 [[Jews]] and 96 with another religion.<ref name="population"/>

'''Other'''<br/ >
Out of the 56,987 age 16 or over in 2001, 43.81% were married, 26.26% [[Single person|single]], 9.57% [[widow]]ed, 9.36% [[divorce]]d, 8.98% re-married and 2.01% separated (but still legally married).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=276911&c=LA14+3LD&d=13&e=13&g=431977&i=1x1003x1004&o=50&m=0&r=0&s=1193305134031&enc=1&dsFamilyId=9 | title = marital Status Barrow-in-Furness| accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref> The [[Total Fertility Rate]] of Barrow is 1.54, lower than [[North West England]]'s rate (1.66) and England's (1.65).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=276911&c=LA14+3LD&d=13&e=13&g=431977&i=1x1003x1004&o=50&m=0&r=0&s=1193305134046&enc=1&dsFamilyId=826 | title = Fertility rate of Barrow-in-Furness| accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref>
162 Barrovians were working in the [[Armed Forces]] in 2001<ref>{{cite web | url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=276911&c=LA14+3LD&d=13&e=13&g=431977&i=1x1003x1004&o=50&m=0&r=0&s=1193305134031&enc=1&dsFamilyId=191 | title = Barrovians in the Armed Forces | accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref> Barrow has one of the highest percentages of people on benefits in the entire United Kingdom, at 23% of the working age, it is almost double England's average of 14%.<ref>[http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=276911&c=Barrow&d=13&e=46&g=431960&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1202747320406&enc=1&dsFamilyId=1623 Neighbourhood Statistics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

==Economy==
===Shipyard===
[[Image:BAE Systems from Walney.jpg|thumb|right|BAE Systems viewed from Walney Island]]
The [[BAE Systems Submarine Solutions]] shipyard at Barrow is one of the largest shipyards in [[Great Britain|Britain]]. It was expanded in 1986 by construction of a new covered assembly facility, the Devonshire Dock Hall (DDH), completed by [[Alfred McAlpine|Alfred McAlpine plc]], on land that was created by infilling part of the Devonshire Dock with 2.4 million tonnes of sand pumped from nearby Roosecote Sands.<ref>The Road to Success: Alfred McAlpine 1935 - 1985 page 174, Tony Gray, Rainbird Publishing, 1987</ref> DDH is the tallest building in Cumbria at 51&nbsp;m. With a length of 268 m (879 ft), width of 51 m (167 ft) and an area of {{convert|25000|m2|sqft|}} it is the largest shipbuilding construction complex of its kind in Europe.<ref>[http://www.baesystems.com/Newsroom/NewsReleases/2006/press_15052006.html BAE Systems Press Release]</ref> 

The DDH provides a controlled environment for ship and submarine assembly, and avoids the difficulties caused by building on the slope of traditional [[slipway]]s. Outside the hall, a 24,300 tonne capacity shiplift allows completed vessels to be lowered into the water independently of the tide. Vessels can also be lifted out of the water and transferred to the hall.<ref>{{cite paper | author = BAE Systems| title = Devonshire Dock Hall (DDH): One of the most advanced Shipbuilding Complexes in the World | url = http://www.baesystems.com/BAEProd/groups/public/documents/ss_asset/bae_subs_ddhdatasheet.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate = 2007-06-03 }}</ref> The first use of the DDH was for construction of the [[Vanguard class submarine|''Vanguard''-class]] submarines, and later vessels of the [[Trafalgar class submarine|''Trafalgar''-class]] submarines were also built there. The shipyard is currently constructing the [[Astute class submarine|''Astute''-class submarines]] the first of which was launched on 8 June 2007.<ref name="Astute_launch">{{cite news | title = New UK nuclear submarine launched | publisher = [[BBC News]] | date = 8 June 2007 | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6733777.stm | accessdate = 2007-06-14}}</ref> BAE is currently studying the design of a [[British replacement of the Trident system|new class]] of ballistic missile submarines. BAE also has orders for submarine pressure domes for the [[Spanish Navy]].<ref name="Spanish_subs">{{cite news | title = BAE lands submarine export order | publisher = [[BBC News]] | date = 2 May 2007 | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6615139.stm | accessdate = 2007-06-14}}</ref>

BAE Systems has obtained planning permission from Barrow Borough Council for the new Central Assembly Shop dubbed 'Son of DDH' which will provide over 700 new jobs, initially in construction of a large section of the new [[Queen Elizabeth class aircraft carrier]]s. (hull lower block 3).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/FactSheets/EquipmentFactsheets/FactsheetTheRoyalNavysFutureAircraftCarriers.htm |title= FACTSHEET: The Royal Navy's Future Aircraft Carriers | accessdate=2007-09-23 |date= 2007-07-25|publisher= [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=531927|title= Go-Ahead for Son of DDH|accessdate=2007-08-15 |date= 2007-08-14|publisher= [[North West Evening Mail]]}}</ref> Despite the large fall in numbers employed by the shipyard, Barrow retains a high proportion of workers in the manufacturing industry. In September 2008, Barrow was named as the most [[working class]] location in the UK, based on a series of measures devised to judge the lifestyle of the people. Ironically in the 1870s Barrow had more aristocrats per head than anywhere else in the country.<ref>[http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/1.244620 http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/1.244620]</ref>

[[Image:HMSBulwarkL15.jpg|thumb|right|[[HMS Bulwark (L15)|HMS ''Bulwark'']] of the [[Albion class landing platform dock|''Albion''-class]] [[landing platform dock]]s.]]
The shipyard does not build submarines exclusively: it undertook fitting out and commissioning of helicopter carrier [[HMS Ocean (L12)|HMS ''Ocean'']] in the mid-1990s (although the ship was built by Kv<U+00E6>rner in [[Govan]], [[Glasgow]]), and construction of [[Wave Knight class tanker|Wave Class tanker]] [[RFA Wave Knight (A389)|''Wave Knight'']] and [[Albion class landing platform dock|Albion Class]] amphibious assault ships [[HMS Albion (L14)|HMS ''Albion'']] and [[HMS Bulwark (L15)|HMS ''Bulwark'']].[[Image:Astute2cropped.jpg|thumb|left|[[HMS Astute (S119)|HMS Astute]] is the most recent vessel to be launched in Barrow]].

===Other===
[[Associated British Ports Holdings]] owns and operates the port of Barrow which can berth vessels up to {{convert|200|m|ft|abbr=on}} long and with a [[draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|10|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Principal traffic includes the export of condensate by-product from the production of gas at the Rampside Gas Terminal, [[wood pulp]], and locally quarried limestone which is exported to Scandinavia for use in the paper industry. The port, which has deep water access, also handles the shipment of nuclear [[nuclear fuel|fuels]] and [[radioactive waste|waste]] for [[BNFL]]'s nearby [[Sellafield]] plant.<ref>{{cite web | publisher= Associated British Ports  | title = Port of Barrow | url=http://www.abports.co.uk/custinfo/ports/barrow.htm | accessdate = 2007-08-20 }}</ref>

In 1985, gas was discovered in [[Morecambe Bay]], with the products processed onshore at the gas terminal in Rampside, south of the town.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=459 | title = About Us | publisher = Centrica Gas | accessdate=2007-07-21 }}</ref> A new 30 turbine [[wind turbine|wind-farm]] which has recently been built in the [[Irish Sea]] off the coast of [[Walney Island]], although the electricity generated is sent by undersea cable to [[Heysham]].<ref>{{cite press release | title = First power generated by Barrow offshore wind farm | date = 2006-06-03 | publisher = DONG Energy | url = http://www.dongenergy.com/en/pr/pressemeddelelser/2006/data/foerste+produktion+af+el+fra+barrow+havmollepark.htm | accessdate = 2007-07-21 }}</ref>

[[James Fisher & Sons]] plc, a service provider in all sectors of the [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] industry and a specialist supplier of engineering services to the [[nuclear power|nuclear]] industry in the UK and abroad,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.james-fisher.co.uk/|title= Welcome to James Fisher|accessdate=2007-08-30 |year= 2005|work= James Fisher official website|publisher= James Fisher and Sons}}</ref> was founded in Barrow in 1847<ref>{{cite news |first= Mary|last= MacIsaac|title= With a fair wind blowing there are profits to be made on the high seas|url= http://business.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=895&id=401272003|work= Armchair Investor|publisher= [[The Scotsman]]|date=  2003-04-06|accessdate=2007-08-30 }}</ref> and is the largest company to have its [[headquarters]] situated in [[Cumbria]].{{Fact|date=August 2007}} Annual revenue stood at almost [[<U+00A3>]]90 million in 2007 (up 55[[%]] from <U+00A3>57 million in 2006), as well as staff numbers standing at over 1,000 worldwide, with 120 of those in the Barrow headquarters.<ref>{{cite news |title= Jobs Hope as Fisher Booms|url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=536629|publisher= [[North West Evening Mail]]|date=  2007-08-29|accessdate=2007-08-30 }}</ref>

Other major employers include the [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]], through Furness General Hospital, which employs 1,800 staff<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nwra.gov.uk/downloads/documents/imported/321089760698.doc | title=Cumbria Prosperity Priorities Summit held on 2 April 2004 | publisher=North West Regional Assembly | accessdate=2007-08-20 | format=[[DOC (computing)|DOC]]}}</ref> and the [[Kimberly Clark]] paper mill which has 400 employees.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.furnessenterprise.co.uk/furness_enterprise_sectors.asp?menuID=13&ID=IS6 | title= Furness Enterprise - Fast Moving Consumer Goods | publisher=Furness Enterprise | accessdate=2007-08-20}}</ref> Amongst many retailers that have established themselves in Barrow, the [[furniture]] store [[Stollers]] is noted as being one of the largest shops of its kind in the UK.

