===Tourism===
[[Image:Rampside.jpeg|thumb|An example of the scenery, just south of the town in [[Rampside]]]]
Being only around 20 minutes from the [[Lake District]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.totaltravel.co.uk/travel/north-west/carlisle-cumbrian-coast/south-cumbria/travel-guides/Destinations/barrow-in-furness |title= Barrow in Furness|accessdate=2007-08-14 |publisher= totaltravel.com}}</ref> Barrow has been referred to as a 'gateway to the lakes',<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=467814|title= Half Term Fun for the Kids Just on the Doorstep|accessdate=2007-08-14 |date= 2007-02-17|publisher= [[North West Evening Mail]]}}</ref> a status which could be enhanced by the new [[marina]] complex and planned [[cruise ship]] [[Dock (maritime)|terminal]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/docs/November%202005%20-%20Executive%20Committee%20Agenda.doc|title= November 2005 - Executive Committee Agenda|accessdate=2007-08-14 |year= 2005|month= November|format= [[DOC (computing)|DOC]]|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|pages= 5}}</ref> Barrow itself has several tourist attractions, including the [[Dock Museum]]. The museum tells the history of Barrow's shipbuilding, as well as offering gallery space to local artists and schoolchildren. It is built upon and around the old graving dock.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/enjoy_cumbria/places/barrow_dock_museum.shtml|title= Barrow Dock Museum|accessdate=2007-08-14 |work= Enjoy Cumbria|publisher= BBC}}</ref> Barrow also has a popular indoor market, which features a food hall as well as stalls selling clothes and other goods.<ref>{{cite news | first=Bibi | last=van der Zee | coauthors= | title=Pitch Perfect, Part Two | date=2007-08-07 | publisher= The Guardian| url =http://www.guardian.co.uk/g2/story/0,,1838907,00.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2007-07-27 | language = }}</ref><ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=149 |title=Barrow Borough Council - Barrow Markets |accessdate=2007-07-27 |date=2007-03-07 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council }}</ref> Barrow has been described as the Lake District's premier shopping town, with big name shops mingling in with small local ones,<ref name="aboutbritain">{{cite web |url= http://www.aboutbritain.com/towns/barrow-in-furness.asp|title= Barrow-in-Furness Tourist Information|accessdate=2007-08-25 |publisher= AboutBritain.com}}</ref> and being home to [[Portland Walk Shopping Centre]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=161|title= Shopping and Town Centre|accessdate=2007-09-23 |publisher= Barrow Borough Council}}</ref> The town also features Hollywood Park - a leisure facility with restaurants, shops<ref name="aboutbritain"/> and Cumbria's largest [[Cinema (place)|cinema]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=137|title= Exploring the Area around Barrow-in-Furness|accessdate=2007-09-23 |publisher= Barrow Borough Council}}</ref> The town also features several other [[retail parks]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.barrow.furness.co.uk/barrow_lifestyle.asp?ID=L6|title= 24 Hour Shopping|accessdate=2007-08-30 |work= Barrow. Furness.co.uk|publisher= Furness Enterprise Ltd.}}</ref> The Park Leisure Centre is a fitness suite with a pool, set in the {{convert|45|acre|ha|sing=on}} Barrow Park.<ref name="aboutbritain"/> Walney Island is home to two world renound nature reserves as well as several golf courses, and historically [[Furness Abbey]] on the outskirts of Barrow was once the second richest and most powerful cisterian abbey in the entire country. Both locations are significant tourist draws.

==Transport==
''' ''See:'' ''' [[:Category:Transport in Barrow-in-Furness|Transport in Barrow-in-Furness]]
===Roads===
Barrow's principal road link is the [[A590 road|A590]], linking it to [[Ulverston]], the [[Lake District]] and to the [[M6 motorway]].<ref name="Map">{{cite web |url= http://maps.google.co.uk/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Barrow+in+Furness&ie=UTF8&ll=54.173287,-2.999268&spn=0.205782,0.6427&z=11&om=1|title= Barrow area map|accessdate=2007-08-26 |format= Flash|work= [[Google Maps]]|publisher= [[Google]]}}</ref> Just north of Barrow is the southern terminus of the [[A595 road|A595]], linking the town to [[Whitehaven]], [[Workington]] and eventually [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]].<ref name="Map"/> The possibility of a bridge link over [[Morecambe Bay]] is occasionally raised, with feasibility studies currently underway.<ref>{{cite news | last = Hetherington | first = Peter | title = Council gives thumbs up to <span style="white-space:nowrap">12&nbsp;mile&nbsp;(19&nbsp;km)</span> bridge for Morecambe Bay | work = The Guardian | date = 19 May 2004 | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,3604,1220030,00.html | accessdate = 2007-03-09 }}</ref> [[Walney Bridge]] connects Barrow Island to [[Walney Island]].

===Buses===
Bus services within the town are operated by [[Stagecoach North West]]. There is no specifically designated bus station, although many buses start and terminate their routes near the town hall. The original [[bus station|bus depot]] was known for its role in a [[1970s]] television commercial for [[Chewits]] sweets before its demolition.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/content/articles/2006/03/30/cumbriaonfilm_chewits_feature.shtml | title=Barrow Chewits ad | publisher=BBC Cumbria | accessdate = 2007-07-17 }}</ref> Other services link Barrow with outlying villages as well as longer distance routes to [[Dalton-in-Furness]], [[Ulverston]] and [[Kendal]].

===Railways===
[[Barrow-in-Furness railway station]] provides connections to [[Whitehaven]], [[Workington]] and [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] to the north, via the [[Cumbrian Coast Line]] and to [[Ulverston]], [[Grange-over-Sands]] and [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] to the east, via the [[Furness Line]]. It handles 503,800 passengers annually.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/upload/xls/station_usage_2005-06.xls | title= Station entries and exits 2005/6 | publisher= Office of the Rail Regulator | accessdate=2007-07-23 | format=xls}}</ref> Barrow has a second [[railway station]], called [[Roose railway station]], which serves the suburb of [[Roose]].

[[Furness Abbey]], Barrow's third main line station, closed in 1950. There was also a station on [[Barrow Island]], used to enable workers at [[Vickers Limited]] (as it was then known) to commute directly between the shipyard and nearby towns served by the [[Furness Railway]]. This railway link was severed in 1966 when the famous cradle bridge across the docks was closed permanently for safety reasons.

===Other transport===
Other means of transport in and out of Barrow include air (in the 1980s Furness Air was an airline which made it available for Barrovians to commute to Manchester Intl.), with the town being home to a regional [[airfield]] ([[Barrow/Walney Island Airfield]]) which operate two Beechkraft Kingair 250 aircraft which fly to various routes every weekday including: Manchester Intl., Bristol and Blackpool intl, owned and operated by [[BAE Systems]] ([[IATA airport code]]: BWF, [[ICAO]]: EGNL), the longest runway is almost 4,000 feet long. It is one of two airports in the county, the other being [[Carlisle Airport]]. The nearest international airport is [[Blackpool International Airport]], although most people from Barrow use the larger [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport|Liverpool]] and [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]] airports. Despite being one of the UK's leading shipbuilding centres, Barrow is only a minor [[port]]. Although there are no [[ferry]] links to Barrow, there are proposals to create a cruise ship terminal.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/4706191.stm | title="Town chosen for cruise ship terminal" | publisher=BBC | accessdate=2007-06-15 }}</ref>

==Sport==
'''Barrow A.F.C.'''

{{Main|Barrow A.F.C.}}
[[Barrow A.F.C.]] are in the [[Conference National]] division of English football.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=151|title= Sports in Barrow and Furness|accessdate=2007-08-19 |publisher= Barrow Borough Council}}</ref> The team, founded in 1901, are nicknamed "the Bluebirds" and play their home games at the [[Holker Street]] stadium.<ref name="Bluebirds">{{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/sport/clubs/barrow/12_2003.shtml|title= Barrow Football Club|accessdate=2007-08-19 |publisher= BBC}}</ref> The side were members of the [[Football League]] until they were demoted in 1972.<ref name="Bluebirds"/> In 1990, they won the [[FA Trophy]] beating [[Leek Town F.C.|Leek Town]] 3-0 in the final at [[Wembley Stadium (1924)|Wembley Stadium]], London.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.napit.co.uk/viewus/infobank/football/fatophy.php|title= The FA Trophy|accessdate=2007-08-19 |publisher= Napit.co.uk}}</ref> Football players born in Barrow include England internationals [[Emlyn Hughes]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2004/11/10/db1001.xml|title=  Emlyn Hughes Obituary|accessdate=2007-07-08 |date=  2004-11-11|work= Telegraph.co.uk|publisher= [[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref> and [[Gary Stevens]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.toffeeweb.com/history/legends/Stevens.asp|title= Stevens, Gary 1981-88|accessdate=2007-07-08 |last= Pike|first= Richard|coauthors= Poutianinen, Marko|year= 1999|work= Hall of Fame|publisher= ToffeeWeb}}</ref> as well as [[Harry Hadley]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.englandstats.com/playerreport.php?pid=424 | title = Player Report - Harry Hadley | accessdate = 2007-07-21 |publisher= EnglandStats.com}}</ref> and [[Vic Metcalfe]].<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.englandstats.com/playerreport.php?pid=659 |title=Player Profile - Vic Metcalfe |accessdate=2007-08-07 |publisher=EnglandStats.com }}</ref>
Of current professional footballers, [[Wayne Curtis]],<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | title=Wayne makes Wembley History | date=2007-05-21 | publisher=[[CN Group]] | url =http://www.nwemail.co.uk/unknown/viewarticle.aspx?id=500925 | work =[[North West Evening Mail]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-08-07 | language = }}</ref> [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]] striker, and Iran Under-20 and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] winger [[Shana Haji]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.persianmirror.com/Article_det.cfm?id=1367&getArticleCategory=42&getArticleSubCategory=4|title= Shana Haji, the first Iranian player in Scotland|accessdate=2007-06-21 |last= Dastafshan|first= Afshin|publisher= Persian Mirror}}</ref> both hail from the town.

'''Holker Old Boys F.C.'''

{{Main|Holker Old Boys F.C.}}

Holker Old Boys, based at Rakesmoor Lane, are the town's second most successful football team, and they play in the [[North West Counties Football League]] Division One.

'''Barrow RLFC'''

{{Main|Barrow Raiders}}
[[Rugby league]] is a well-established sport and the town is considered as one of the game's traditional heartlands at professional and amateur levels.<ref name="rugby">{{cite news |first=Andy |last=Wilson |title=RUGBY LEAGUE: CARLISLE MERGER SIGNALS RETHINK |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=1997-10-16 |accessdate=2007-08-20 |page=27 |quote=Now Carlisle's decision to move in with Barrow, a traditional hotbed of league where the amateur game remains as strong as ever, may be followed by a new club from [[South Wales]] entering Super League next year.}}</ref> The professional team, [[Barrow Raiders|Barrow]], whose home games are at [[Craven Park (Barrow)|Craven Park]], play in [[Co-operative Championship|The Championship]]. In the 1950s the side played in three Challenge Cup finals, winning the last of these against [[Workington Town]]. In the 1997 reorganisation of the sport the original Barrow RLFC team merged with [[Carlisle RLFC|Carlisle Border Raiders]] to form Barrow Border Raiders,<ref>{{cite news |first=Andy |last=Wilson |title=RUGBY LEAGUE: CARLISLE MERGER SIGNALS RETHINK |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=1997-10-16 |accessdate=2007-08-20 |page=27 |quote=CARLISLE and Barrow have decided to merge into a new club, Barrow Border Raiders, with repercussions extending well beyond the Second Division and Cumbria.}}</ref> with the word "border" later dropped. Players who were born in the town and played at a professional level include brothers [[Ade Gardner|Ade]]<ref>{{cite news | title = Gardner out for indefinite period | publisher = BBC News | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_league/6599411.stm | date = [[2007-04-27]] | accessdate = 2007-07-21 }}</ref> and [[Mat Gardner]]<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Burke |title= A Welcome MAT For My Mate ADE; HUDDERSFIELD GIANTS V ST HELENS, TOMORROW, KICK-OFF 3PM |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=[[Mirror Group Newspapers]] | page=57 |date=2006-03-11 |accessdate=2007-08-20 |quote=Mat, brought up in Barrow with Ade, said:"It's always been a dream of mine to play against my elder brother and this could be the time it becomes a reality. There's also a big chance we could be meeting head-on on the wing and that would be fantastic. I was pleased with my performance at [[Wakefield Trinity Wildcats|Wakefield Trinity]], I just hope Jon Sharp was pleased too - that's obviously the key to me playing against Saints."}}</ref>  and [[Willie Horne]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/goingout/viewarticle.aspx?id=326017|title= Vickerstown Cricket Club, Walney|accessdate=2007-06-21 |date=  2006-01-26|publisher= [[North West Evening Mail]]}}</ref> The latter captained Barrow to their Challenge Cup victory and represented Great Britain at an international level. He was inducted in to the "Barrow Hall of Fame" along with former Barrow players [[Phil Jackson (rugby league born 1932)|Phil Jackson]] and [[Jimmy Lewthwaite]].<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.rl1908.com/Legends/jackson.htm |title=Rugby League History - Interview with Phil Jackson |accessdate=2007-08-04 |last=Fagan |first=Sean |work=RL1908.com }}</ref>

'''Motorcycle Racing'''

{{Main|Barrow Bombers}}

Barrow-in-Furness has staged speedway racing at three venues since the pioneer days in the late 1920s. The first track was at Holker Street. This venue had a revival for a short spell in the early to mid 1970s. In 1930 the sport moved to Little Park but this a somewhat hazy venue. The sport had a revival in 1978 at Park Avenue Industrial Estate but this was relatively short lived.

'''Golf'''

Barrow is home to two large golf clubs. Barrow Golf Club, founded in 1922, is situated in Hawcoat and covers some {{convert|6209|yd|m|}} with 18 holes.<ref>[http://www.englishgolf-courses.co.uk/cumbria/barrow.php Barrow Golf Club, Cumbria<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Furness Golf Club founded in 1872 is the sixth oldest golf club in England and is possibly the more famous of the two.It is located on Walney Island, just {{convert|50|yd|m|}} from the Irish Sea. It also offers an 18-hole course, a shop and other facilities.<ref>[http://www.golftoday.co.uk/clubhouse/coursedir/cumbria/furness.html Furness Golf Club, Barrow In Furness, Cumbria, England]</ref>

==Culture==
[[Image:Thecanteen.jpg|thumb|right|The rustic entrance to The Canteen]]

===Dialect===
{{Unreferenced|date=June 2009}}
Barrow is unique within Cumbria and the local dialect tends to be more [[Lancashire]]-oriented. Like [[Liverpool]], this is due to the large numbers of settlers from various regions (including predominantly Scotland, elsewhere in England and [[Ireland]] amongst other locations). In general the ''Barrovian'' dialect tends to drop certain letters (including ''h'' and ''t''); for example holiday could be pronounced as '' 'oliday'', and with the drop of the ''h'' there is more emphasis on the letter ''o''.  This can also be seen with the word "hiya" which could be pronounced " 'iya" with a lot of emphasis on the letter ''i''. Another example is with the letter ''t'' where twenty is often pronounced "twen'y" (again an emphasis on the ''n'' could occur); see [[Cumbrian dialect]] as well as [[Lancashire dialect and accent|Lancashire dialect]] for more information.

===Nightlife===

There are countless [[pub]]s and [[working men's club]]s located across Barrow<U+2014>Barrow has fourteen of the latter, one of the highest number per capita of any British town.<ref>http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2008/10/06/barrow-in-furness-the-working-class-capital-of-britain-115875-20779478/</ref> There are also many [[bar (establishment)|bar]]s and [[club]]s found primarily in [[Barrow Town Centre]] on Duke Street and Cornwallis Street. Popular venues on Duke Street include the following bars: Chambers, The Lounge, Bar Cairo, [[Yates's]]. Cornwallis Street <U+2013> often dubbed the ''[[Gaza Strip]]'' by locals <U+2013> is currently undergoing a multi-million pound renovation with the former Martinis being the flagship renovation into Club M. Other clubs on Cornwallis Street include: Circus Circus, Kavannas, O'Sullivans, Scorpio and the nearby floating Blue Lagoon Nightclub which has multiple floors like many other Barrow clubs although with a capacity of {{formatnum:2400}} it is the town's largest club.

===Music===

Barrow has produced several musical performers of note. They include [[Thomas Round]], a singer and actor in D'Oyly Carte productions of [[Savoy Opera]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diamond.boisestate.edu/GaS/whowaswho/R/RoundThomas.htm |title=Thomas Round |accessdate=2007-08-07 |publisher=Boise State University }}</ref> as well as [[Glenn Cornick]], the original [[bass guitar]]ist in the rock band [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]].<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.j-tull.com/musicians/pastmembers/glenncornick.html |title=Glenn Cornick |accessdate=2007-08-07 |publisher=The Official Jethro Tull Website }}</ref> The father of [[Simply Red]]'s [[Mick Hucknall]] was born in Barrow before moving to [[Manchester]].<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | title=Hucknall becomes a father | date=2007-06-21 | publisher=[[CN Group]] | url =http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=512465 | work =[[North West Evening Mail]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-08-21 | language = |quote=The flame-haired singer, 47, toured BAE's shipyard with his father Reg Hucknall, who was born in Barrow and grew up in the town before moving to Manchester. Young Mick Hucknall spent many family holidays in Barrow where many of his relatives still live. }}</ref> In addition, Paul MacKenzie, bass player with 1980s [[Preston]]-based [[thrash metal]] band [[Xentrix]], is from Barrow <ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.metalist.co.il/interviewprivate.asp?id=141&lang=eng | title=Metalist Magazine | accessdate=2009-01-10}}</ref>. More recently, hip-hop [[DJ]] and record producer [[Aim (musician)|Aim]] has had considerable commercial success.<ref>{{cite news | first=David | last=Sue | coauthors= | title=Superstar DJ continues to Aim high | date=2006-06-23 | publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] | url =http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/rock_and_pop/s/216/216434_superstar_dj_continues_to_aim_high.html | work =[[Manchester Evening News]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-08-07 | language = }}</ref>
Les Muscutt, jazz banjo player and guitarist was born in Barrow in Furness in 1942. The family moved to East Ham in London where Les became a professional musician at age 15.

Shortly after the [[Second World War]] an Old Tyme Dancing trio was formed by Wyn Large ([[piano]]), Felix Lee ([[piano accordion]]) and Reg Powell ([[drums]]). This group entertained three or more times a week at several venues in the town and surrounding districts and was very popular with those locals who enjoyed keeping Old Tyme dancing alive. Wyn Large was succeeded by [[Billy]] Steele in the 1960s after which the group became known as the Felix Lee Trio until it disbanded in the 1970s due to its ageing members.

===Expressive arts===
[[Image:Holiday2005b 052.jpg|thumb|The [[Duddon Valley]], just outside of Barrow]]

Several people of note in the world of Art and Literature have come from Barrow. Artist [[Keith Tyson]], who won the [[Turner Prize]] in 2002, was born in nearby [[Ulverston]] and attended the Barrow-in-Furness College of Engineering as well as working at then [[VSEL]] shipyard.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://collection.britishcouncil.org/html/artist/artist.aspx?id=19092 |title=Keith Tyson Biography |accessdate=2007-08-04 |publisher=[[British Council]] }}</ref> [[Constance Spry]], the author and florist who revolutionised interior design in the [[U.K]] in the 1930s and 40's, moved to the town with her son Anthony during [[World War I]] to work as welfare supervisor.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.designmuseum.org/design/constance-spry |title=Constance Spry / Florist, Author + Social Reformer (1886 - 1960) |accessdate=2007-08-04 |publisher=Design Museum }}</ref> [[Peter Purves]], later a [[Blue Peter]] presenter, began his acting career with 2 years as a member of the Renaissance Theatre Company at the town's Her Majesty's Theatre.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.peterpurves.com/inthetheatre.html |title=Peter Purves in the Theatre |accessdate=2007-08-04 |publisher=peterpurves.com }}</ref>
The Canteen Media & Arts Centre - known simply as "The Canteen" - and [[Forum 28|Forum Twenty Eight]] are the main venues for theatre.

===Literature===
In fictional works, Barrow and [[Vickerstown]] on [[Walney Island]] featured in children's show ''[[The Railway Series]]'', which developed into ''[[Thomas the Tank Engine]]'', as the point where the fictional [[Sodor (fictional island)|Island of Sodor]] connected to mainland Britain and the national rail network.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.storybookengland.com/authors.php?form_id=3413682892|title= Thomas the Tank Engine books|accessdate=2007-08-25 |publisher= Storybook England}}</ref>

The great Portuguese poet [[Fernando Pessoa]] wrote a poem called "Barrow-in-Furness". His "heteronym" [[<U+00C1>lvaro de Campos]] lived in Barrow when he was studying ship engineering.

===Architecture===
[[Image:Ramsdensquare.jpg|thumb|left|Ramsden Square in [[Barrow]] [[town centre]] is home to many fine buildings including Barrow Public Library]]

Barrow is one of Britain's few [[planned town]]s and has many fine buildings to show for it.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.enjoyengland.com/destinations/find/englands-northwest/cumbria/barrow-in-furness.aspx |title=Destination guide for Barrow-in-Furness |accessdate=2007-08-08 |publisher=Enjoy England }}</ref> There are many old and distinctive buildings in the town centre, mostly from the [[Victorian era]], such as the [[town hall]], old [[fire station]], the 'Nan Tait' Centre, [[Salvation Army]] building and [[public library]]. There is also an increasing number of modern [[office building]]s as well as the [[shipyard]]'s [[Cranes (machine)|cranes]] and [[construction]] halls which dominate much of Barrow's skyline. Barrow has 8 [[Grade I listed buildings]] (see: [[List of Grade I listed buildings in Cumbria#Barrow in Furness|List of Grade I listed buildings in Barrow-in-Furness]]), 15 [[Listed building|Grade II*]] and 249 [[Grade II]] buildings.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2758 |title=Listed Buildings |accessdate=2007-08-16 |publisher= Barrow Borough Council}}</ref>

===Media===
====Radio====
Barrow is served by one [[commercial radio]] station, [[The Bay (radio station)|The Bay]], which is broadcast from [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] and serves the area around [[Morecambe Bay]]. Another commercial station, [[Abbey FM]], ceased broadcasting in February 2009 when it went into administration.<ref>{{cite news|title= Abbey FM ceases broadcasting|url= http://radiotoday.co.uk/news.php?extend.4343.2| accessdate= 24 February, 2009| date= [[2009]]-[[01-30]]| publisher= ''Radio Today''}}</ref> The [[BBC]]'s local radio service is [[BBC Radio Cumbria]], who have studio facilities in the town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/content/articles/2005/10/19/barrow_office_feature.shtml |title=BBC - Cumbria - Local Radio - The Barrow Office. |accessdate=2007-08-16 |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref>

====Newspapers====
There is one paid-for evening daily paper, the ''[[North West Evening Mail]]''. There is also a weekly freesheet called the ''Advertiser'', which is delivered to most households in the Furness area. Both are owned by independent publisher the [[CN group]], formerly Cumbrian Newspapers.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cngroup.co.uk/publishing/index.html | title=CN Group - Publishing | accessdate=2007-06-10 }}</ref>

==== Television ====
Barrow lies in the [[Granada TV]] <U+2013> [[North West England]] region with the main signal coming from the [[Winter Hill transmitting station|Winter Hill]] transmitter near Bolton. There is also a relay transmitter at [[Millom]] whose signal can be received in the northern end of the town. The signal from Millom is generally of inferior quality, with most households receiving BBC 1 and 2 and ITV at adequate quality, with low quality reception of Channel 4 programs.

Various television personalities were born in the district. Dave Myers was a [[motorcycle|biker]] born in Barrow, before he found fame as one half of [[Celebrity chef|television cookery]] duo [[The Hairy Bikers]].<ref>{{cite news | first=Rosanna | last=Greenstreet | coauthors= | title=My Home: Dave Myers of the Hairy Bikers | date=2006-05-10 | publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] | url =http://money.independent.co.uk/property/homes/article363011.ece | work =[[The Independent]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-08-07 | language = }}</ref> [[Karen Taylor (comedian)|Karen Taylor]] is a TV [[comedienne]] best known for her [[BBC Three]] sketch show ''[[Touch Me, I'm Karen Taylor]]''.<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | title=Karen's sketch show opens | date=2007-06-11 | publisher=[[CN Group]] | url =http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508863 | work =[[North West Evening Mail]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-07-25 | language = }}</ref> [[Steve Dixon (newsreader)|Steve Dixon]] is a [[News presenter|newsreader]] for [[Sky News]],<ref>{{cite news | first=Cassandra | last=Jardine | coauthors= | title='Diabetes is not as simple as it appears' | date=2003-11-03 | publisher= | url =http://www.telegraph.co.uk/global/main.jhtml?xml=/global/2003/11/03/hdiab03.xml | work =[[The Daily Telegraph]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-08-07 | language = }}</ref> while [[Nigel Kneale]] was a well-known film and television scriptwriter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article622130.ece|title=Nigel Kneale|publisher=[[The Times]]|date=2006-11-02|accessdate=2007-02-08|page=71}}</ref>

Wartime diarist and local housewife [[Nella Last]]'s memoirs were adapted for television, with parts of the town used in filming. The resulting programme, ''[[Housewife, 49]]'', starring comedienne [[Victoria Wood]], was broadcast by [[ITV]] in 2006. It won two [[British Academy Television Awards 2007|BAFTA]] awards - one for Best Single Drama, the other for Best Actress (Victoria Wood).<ref>{{cite news | first=Ian | last=Wylie | coauthors= | title=Victoria plays it straight | date=2006-12-01 | publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] | url =http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/film_and_tv/s/229/229723_victoria_plays_it_straight.html | work =[[Manchester Evening News]] | pages = | accessdate = 2007-08-05 | language = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=481129|title= Top Award for Diary Drama Set in Barrow|accessdate=2007-08-14 |date= 2007-03-27|publisher= [[North West Evening Mail]]}}</ref>
[[CITV]] children's show [[The Treacle People]] had two villains named Barrow and [[Furness]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.channel4.com/learning/microsites/T/treacle/series2.html | publisher =[[Channel 4]] | accessdate=2007-05-10 | title=Treacle People microsite }}</ref>
* In addition to that the first episode of Nature Boy was filmed at Walney School.

== Education ==
{|class="infobox" align="centre"
|-
|colspan="2" align="center"|[[Nursery school]]s||colspan="2" align="center"|13
|-
|colspan="2" align="center"|[[Infant school]]s||colspan="2" align="center"|5
|-
|colspan="2" align="center"|[[Junior school]]s||colspan="2" align="center"|5
|-
|colspan="2" align="center"|[[Primary school]]s||colspan="2" align="center"|15
|-
|colspan="2" align="center"|[[Secondary school]]s||colspan="2" align="center"|5
|-
|colspan="2" align="center"|[[Private school]]s||colspan="2" align="center"|1
|-
|colspan="2" align="center"|[[College]]s||colspan="2" align="center"|2
|-
|colspan="2" align="center"|[[University|Universitie]]s||colspan="2" align="center"|1* 
|-
|colspan="2" align="center"|* [[University of Cumbria]] partly sited in Barrow
|}

Education in the state sector is provided by the local education authority, [[Cumbria|Cumbria County Council]]. There are fifteen [[primary school]]s, five [[infant school]]s, five [[junior school]]s and many nurseries. Five [[secondary schools]] were created following the reorganisation of Barrow's selective tri-partite secondary education system in 1979: [[Parkview Community College of Technology|Parkview School]], [[St. Bernard's Catholic High School]], [[Walney School]], [[Thorncliffe School]] and [[Alfred Barrow School]]. Three schools - Parkview, Thorncliffe and Alfred Barrow are scheduled to close in August 2009 with a new Furness Academy due to take their place from the first of September 2009 on the Parkview and Thorncliffe sites - initially in the existing buildings there, which are planned to be replaced by state-of-the-art building on both sites within three years. In addition to publicly funded education, the town has one private school, [[Chetwynde School|Chetwynde]], which has fee-paying pupils from nursery to [[sixth form]] level.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.chetwynde.co.uk/welcome.html|title= Welcome from the Head of School|accessdate=2007-08-18 |last= Nixon|first= Isobel|format= Flash|publisher= Chetwynde School}}</ref>

In the further education sector there are two colleges.<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.barrow.furness.co.uk/barrow_schools.asp?ID=L2 |title=Schools and Education |accessdate=2007-08-17 |work=barrow.furness.co.uk |publisher=Furness Enterprise }}</ref> [[Barrow 6th form|Barrow-in-Furness Sixth Form College]] concentrates on teaching [[A-level]] subjects,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.barrow6fc.ac.uk/About/ProgrammesOfStudy.asp?Area_Title=About|title= Programmes of Study|accessdate=2007-08-18 |publisher= Barrow Sixth Form College}}</ref> while [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]] specialises in vocational courses.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.furness.ac.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=section&id=2&Itemid=2|title= School Leavers|accessdate=2007-08-18 |publisher= Furness College}}</ref> 

The town's main library is the Central [[Library]] in Ramsden Square, situated near the town centre.<ref name="Library">{{cite web |url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=163|title= Libraries and Archives|accessdate=2007-08-18 |publisher= Barrow Borough Council}}</ref> The library was established in 1882 in a room near the town hall, and moved to its current premises in 1922. A branch of the County Archive Service, opened in 1979 and containing many of the town's archives, is located within adjoining premises,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.familia.org.uk/services/england/cumbria_barrow.html|title= Cumbria County Council (Barrow)|accessdate=2007-08-18 |publisher= Familia}}</ref> whilst until 1991 the library also housed the Furness Museum, a forerunner of the [[Dock Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/museum_history.htm|title= Museum History|accessdate=2007-08-18 |format= Flash|publisher= [[Dock Museum]]}}</ref> Smaller branch libraries are currently provided at [[Walney]], [[Roose]], Ormsgill and [[Barrow Island]].<ref name="Library"/>

